05294nam a22007455i 9780674065482DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)840443461  a97806740654827 a10.4159/harvard.97806740654822doi  a(DE-B1597)178214  a(OCoLC)806492775  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQP84.6b.R6413 2012eb 7aSCI0080002bisacsh04a612 .0222231 aRoenneberg, Till, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInternal Time :bChronotypes, Social Jet Lag, and Why You're So Tired /cTill Roenneberg. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (270 p.) :b1 halftone, 40 line illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Worlds Apart -- t2. Of Early Birds and Long Sleepers -- t3. Counting Sheep -- t4. A Curious Astronomer -- t5. The Lost Days -- t6. The Periodic Shift Worker -- t7. The Fast Hamster -- t8. Dawn at the Gym -- t9. The Elusive Transcript -- t10. Temporal Ecology -- t11. Wait until Dark -- t12. The End of Adolescence -- t13. What a Waste of Time! -- t14. Days on Other Planets -- t15. When Will My Organs Arrive? -- t16. The Scissors of Sleep -- t17. Early Socialists, Late Capitalists -- t18. Constant Twilight -- t19. From Frankfurt to Morocco and Back -- t20. Light at Night -- t21. Partnership Timing -- t22. A Clock for All Seasons -- t23. Professional Selection -- t24. The Nocturnal Bottleneck -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly birds and night owls are born, not made. Sleep patterns may be the most obvious manifestation of the highly individualized biological clocks we inherit, but these clocks also regulate bodily functions from digestion to hormone levels to cognition. Living at odds with our internal timepieces, Till Roenneberg shows, can make us chronically sleep deprived and more likely to smoke, gain weight, feel depressed, fall ill, and fail geometry. By understanding and respecting our internal time, we can live better.Internal Time combines storytelling with accessible science tutorials to explain how our internal clocks work—for example, why morning classes are so unpopular and why “lazy” adolescents are wise to avoid them. We learn why the constant twilight of our largely indoor lives makes us dependent on alarm clocks and tired, and why social demands and work schedules lead to a social jet lag that compromises our daily functioning.Many of the factors that make us early or late “chronotypes” are beyond our control, but that doesn’t make us powerless. Roenneberg recommends that the best way to sync our internal time with our external environment and feel better is to get more sunlight. Such simple steps as cycling to work and eating breakfast outside may be the tickets to a good night’s sleep, better overall health, and less grouchiness in the morning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiological rhythms. 0aChronobiology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE  BIOLOGY, CHEMISTRY, GEOSCIENCES  2012z9783110294071oZDB-23-DBE08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET BIOLOGIE, CHEMIE, GEOWISS.  2012z9783110294064oZDB-23-DBC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harva